<br>
Yes, earth pets have a ton of hps. They need them, because the earth pet takes a beating, and takes another beating due to root when when they should be beating on a mobs backside while it flees. Earth has it's uses but it is the least used pet in my book (excluding rage). Yes, that includes the 52+ fire pets. I can find more uses for those than earth pets.<br>
<br>
As an example: 49 fire pet vs 49 earth pet, hunting hillgiants. Try them both out versus a set number of giants, I'd suggest at least 5 each to get a feeling of an average fight. Of course, let fire pet ds itself.  Earth pet will lose a greater percentage of it's life, because it roots the giant when the giant tries to run, causing the earth pet to take more damage. Now since that percentage is out of a larger amount of hps, each percentage point equals more hps lost than the fire pet. This translates into a much longer amount of time waiting for the pet to heal. The fire pet had killed the giant faster due to it's amazing damage shield, got many free hits on the giants back when the giant turned to run, and will take a shorter amount of time to heal each percentage point of health, because each point is worth fewer hps... and it lost fewer % of health too.  Oh you say you'd just reclaim the earth instead of waiting for it to heal? That means you are spending mana recasting pets and mana on DS and BO (unless you have velious pants and robe), when you could be pulling another giant in the time it takes the fire pet to regen it's lost hps. Fire is so superior to earth for soloing (at those levels) that I can't help but laugh when i hear people say they only use earth for soloing.<br>
<br>
Earth is nearly as bad 50+ as well, except fire is no longer the better pet. Air makes a better solo pet at 53, as it takes less damage, doesn't root, and it's stun creates huge aggro even if resisted (meaning you don't need root to save your ass). At 54 on low mobs Water makes a great pet, as it gets a nice nuke, an extra attack from the front or a backstab from the back. Try a little mage kiting if you like, or have it be a blender on low hp mobs.<br>
<br>
<br>
Save your earth pets for chain casting. At that point all you want is a load of hps to take damage while the ds works, and frankly I'd probably use MS2 instead. Same amount of hps and it doesn't stop to root every other round. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uteamnoir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>teamnoir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#333333>(5/23/02 7:27:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthingstokill.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=375.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: WTh is up with fire pets</span><hr size=1> I've been working my way through all the pets.  Started with earth because of the obvious root.  Moved to fire because...<br>
<br>
Fire pet ds is better than what I can cast.  And fire pet getting hit holds aggro, (and thus holds the mob in place), better than earth pet rooting.<br>
<br>
I still try all the pets on each camp.  I've often been surprised by which works well where.<br>
<br>
